text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: The contemplative state of change is characterised by ambivalence. Patients in this state
are aware of the benefits of changing their behaviour, but they are not ready to make
the change yet and also find advantages in their current situation.
In the case of RCRSP, ambivalence can have many forms : “I understand exercise will help
me… But it hurts !”, “Physical activity is probably great, but after a days’ work I need
rest”, “I know my exercise programme will help me, but it’s just not the right time, it will
probably be easier for me next week”. Procrastination is also common at this stage.
Our objective here is to tip the scales !
Contemplative State
Contemplative State :
Ambivalence

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Our goal is to tip the balance, patients should understand how moving and exercising
will help them, and we should make them engage in active rehabilitation !
You can find some more information on this state of change in the upper-right (zoom
with mouse-wheel or pinch), or drag screen to the right to find the videos.
You can also go to the next state by left clicking, swiping, pressing the right arrow or by
using the menu in the top-left !

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: Generally, patients in the pre-contemplative state of change don't realise they have a
problematic behaviour.
In our specific context of exercise as a treatment of RCRSP, the patients in this state
typically think their shoulder problem is anatomical, and the solution will be passive
and/or external (rest, massage, injection, surgery…).
Since patients don’t realise there is a problem, providing them a solution is meaningless.
Our position here will be to simply raise doubts.
Pre-Contemplative State
Pre-Contemplative State :
Raising doubts

text.inkscape:label: Corps Texte
text.tspan: The point of this section is to fight against a patho-anatomical conception of RCRSP.
It is aimed at patients that believe their shoulder condition will improve from passive
modalities.
You can continue to the next section (Contemplative State) or drag the screen to the
right to see this sections videos. You can also zoom to the upper right for more
informations on the pre-contemplative state of change.
Remember you can use the menu in the top-left corner or go to the next/previous slide
(with mouse buttons, arrow keys or swiping) at any time !

The videos provided in this tool can be used independently, but they are
presented here like a path, and they are grouped according to Prochaska and
Diclemente states of change.
Don’t worry if you are unfamiliar with this model, it’s mostly used here as a
way to organise the content. This classification is based on the patient’s state
of mind regarding exercise/physical activity as a treatment for RCRSP. And
there will be some short info on each state of change.
